{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636186"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17571"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10261"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10056"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23981"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAdenosine triphosphate (ATP) is the primary energy currency of cells, providing energy for numerous cellular processes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how ATP provides energy for cellular processes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of new phosphate bonds","Conversion of ADP to ATP","Breaking of adenosine ring structure","Hydrolysis of terminal phosphate bond","Release of adenine base"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EATP provides energy through \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrolysis of its terminal phosphate bond\u003C/strong\u003E. This high-energy phosphoanhydride bond, when broken, releases approximately 30.5 kJ/mol of free energy under physiological conditions. The reaction produces ADP and inorganic phosphate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreaking of adenosine ring structure\u003C/strong\u003E - The adenosine ring remains intact during ATP utilisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of new phosphate bonds\u003C/strong\u003E - Energy is released by breaking bonds, not forming them\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of ADP to ATP\u003C/strong\u003E - This process requires energy input rather than releasing it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of adenine base\u003C/strong\u003E - The adenine base remains attached during ATP hydrolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe energy released from ATP hydrolysis is coupled to energy-requiring processes such as active transport, muscle contraction, and biosynthetic reactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ATP hydrolysis releases energy by breaking the high-energy phosphate bonds, particularly the terminal phosphate bond.","Each ATP molecule contains three phosphate groups, with the terminal phosphate bond having the highest energy.","ATP hydrolysis yields approximately 30.5 kJ/mol of free energy under physiological conditions."],"references":["Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"que